					<h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
					<h5>Has this been done at other hospitals?</h5>
					<p>Yes. Our programme team have visited other hospitals which already use more up-to-date EPR systems. Each system is slightly different as it is adapted for the hospital.</p>
					<h5>How do we know it will work at this Trust?</h5>
					<p>We have held workshops and demonstrations with staff and looked closely at how the systems can be applied to this Trust.</p>
					<h5>How will we train staff to use the new system?</h5>
					<p>The aim is to start training staff over the Spring and Summer of 2015. It will take some time to train all our staff so it's really important that people put time aside to get this training over the next few months. Some staff may also need to update their SMART cards as these need to be correct in order to access the new EPR.</p>
					<h5>Is there a demonstration available to show how the EPR works?</h5>
					<p>Yes, there is a demonstration which describes a patient's journey, called 'William's journey' <a href="../files/williams_story_EPR.pdf" alt="A presentation explaining how an example patient would experience the new system">which can be downloaded here</a>.</p>
					<h5>Is the new EPR system compatibility with the renal proton system?</h5>
					<p>The new EPR system will interface with the current PROTON system in exactly the same way as Patient Centre. With the new Clinical Portal staff will be able to use a single log-on to view all the different departmental systems.</p>
					<h5>Is the Trust going to use electronic prescribing?</h5>
					<p>We are one of nine hospital Trusts evaluating a new electronic inpatient prescribing system which may be implemented as part of our Electronic Patient Record. As part of this assurance process, we have taken part in national testing and evaluation, led by the HSCIC (Health and Social Care Information Centre) which is the national provider of information, data and IT systems across the health and social care sector. A team from the Trust visited University Hospitals of Morecambe Bay NHS Foundation Trust in August to view the inpatient prescribing system in use on a ward.</p>
					<h5>Will the EPR help support the delivery of the 18 week referral to treatment standard?</h5>
					<p>The EPR incorporates the 18 week pathway recording and detailed work is being undertaken with the supplier of the system to confirm that this will meet the Trust's requirements.</p>
					<h5>Each Clinical Nurse Specialist team has their own mode of documenting patient interactions - in clinic, on ward visits and for telephone calls. What plans are there to incorporate these into the electronic systems?</h5>
					<p>These issues will be worked through over the coming months. Some staff will need to change the way they currently work and there may be more than one option for some of these. A Chief Clinical Information Officer (Nursing) and an Operational Change Manager (Nursing) have been appointed (see the Meet the Team section on this website) to ensure the needs of the nursing workforce are known and incorporated into the programme.</p>
					<h5>We currently ask patients to sign a form to consent to an operation or procedure. How will this be done in future? Will this be done electronically too?</h5>
					<p>The consent process will not change. Consent will be taken in clinic as it happens now. The consent form will be retained with any pathway or pre-op documentation and passed through the pre-op and admissions process where consent will be reconfirmed and acknowledged as per the current practice. Electronic consent is likely to be developed in the future, utilising any number of hand held devices or tablets, combined with electronic forms.</p>
					<h5>Is neonatology going to using the new EPR system?</h5>
					<p>The current JAMIS system will stay. Anything staff currently do in the Patient Centre, they will do in the future in the new EPR system.</p>
